WEBVTT

00:00:00.320 --> 00:00:04.320
<v Teacher>So for -<i>ar</i> verbs, we have -<i>amos</i> in the present for <i>we</i>.

00:00:04.320 --> 00:00:11.520
<v Teacher>Now for -<i>er</i> verbs, we have -<i>emos</i> for the <i>we</i>, and for -<i>ir</i> verbs we have -<i>imos</i>.

00:00:11.820 --> 00:00:18.060
<v Teacher>This is the only time in the whole language that we find a difference between -<i>er</i> and -<i>ir</i> verbs.

00:00:18.060 --> 00:00:19.340
<v Teacher>They're one group,

00:00:19.960 --> 00:00:27.080
<v Teacher>but here - and it's the only time in the entire language - we have a difference between the two of them; in the present for we.

00:00:27.080 --> 00:00:31.800
<v Teacher>For -<i>ir</i> verbs we have -<i>imos</i> and for -<i>er</i> verbs we have -<i>emos</i>.

00:00:31.820 --> 00:00:37.180
<v Teacher>So <b>preferir</b>. What do you think that means, <b>preferir</b>?

00:00:37.180 --> 00:00:38.140
<v Student><i>Prefer.</i>

00:00:38.140 --> 00:00:38.620
<v Teacher>Good.

00:00:38.620 --> 00:00:39.980
<v Teacher><i>To prefer.</i> <i>To prefer.</i>

00:00:39.980 --> 00:00:41.420
<v Teacher>We want to think with the “to"

00:00:41.420 --> 00:00:46.060
<v Teacher>whenever the verb ends in an <i>r</i> it's going to help us just to think of that as “to”.

00:00:45.560 --> 00:00:47.320
<v Teacher><i>To prefer</i>. <b>Preferir.</b>

00:00:47.320 --> 00:00:50.360
<v Teacher>So how would you say: <i>I prefer</i>?

00:00:50.440 --> 00:00:51.640
<v Student><b>Prefero.</b>

00:00:51.640 --> 00:00:53.480
<v Teacher>Good. It should be <b>prefero.</b>

00:00:53.480 --> 00:00:54.280
<v Student><b>Prefiero.</b>

00:00:54.280 --> 00:00:57.080
<v Teacher><b>Prefiero.</b> It splits. <b>Prefiero.</b>

00:00:57.080 --> 00:00:58.120
<v Teacher>He prefers:

00:00:59.140 --> 00:01:00.260
<v Student><b>Prefiere.</b>

00:01:00.260 --> 00:01:01.300
<v Teacher><b>Prefiere.</b>

00:01:01.300 --> 00:01:03.380
<v Teacher><i>They</i> or <i>you</i> (plural):

00:01:03.620 --> 00:01:04.739
<v Student><b>Prefieren.</b>

00:01:04.739 --> 00:01:05.300
<v Teacher>Good.

00:01:05.300 --> 00:01:10.820
<v Teacher>How would you say <i>we prefer</i> (and <b>preferir</b> has an -<i>ir</i> ending)?

00:01:11.400 --> 00:01:12.600
<v Student><b>Preferimos.</b>

00:01:12.600 --> 00:01:13.640
<v Teacher><b>Preferimos.</b>

00:01:13.640 --> 00:01:21.880
<v Teacher>So there the -er doesn't split, and also the i of -ir is appearing in the endings for the first time in the present tense.

00:01:21.880 --> 00:01:23.560
<v Teacher><b>Preferimos</b>.

00:01:23.560 --> 00:01:24.840
<v Teacher>Good.

00:01:24.980 --> 00:01:27.700
<v Teacher>What was <i>to come</i>?

00:01:27.700 --> 00:01:32.340
<v Teacher>It had something to do with <i>convenient</i>, when things "with-come".

00:01:33.840 --> 00:01:34.719
<v Student><b>Venir.</b>

00:01:34.719 --> 00:01:35.360
<v Teacher><b>Venir.</b>

00:01:35.360 --> 00:01:38.719
<v Teacher>And how would you say: <i>we come</i> or <i>we're coming</i>?

00:01:38.719 --> 00:01:39.680
<v Student><b>Venimos.</b>

00:01:39.680 --> 00:01:40.719
<v Teacher><b>Venimos.</b>

00:01:40.719 --> 00:01:41.679
<v Teacher>Good.

00:01:41.720 --> 00:01:44.440
<v Teacher><i>To live</i> in Spanish is <b>vivir</b>.

00:01:44.440 --> 00:01:47.320
<v Teacher><i>V-i-v-i-r.</i> <b>Vivir.</b>

00:01:47.320 --> 00:01:48.040
<v Student><b>Vivir.</b>

00:01:48.040 --> 00:01:51.960
<v Teacher>You might know this from <b>viva la revolución</b>,

00:01:51.560 --> 00:02:03.800
<v Teacher>you might have heard that somewhere. <i>Long live </i> <i>the revolution</i>: <b>viva la revolución</b>. Or you might have even heard <b>viva Las Vegas</b>: <i>long live Las </i> <i>Vegas</i>. <b>Vivir</b>: <i>to live</i>.

00:02:03.800 --> 00:02:05.640
<v Teacher>How do you say: <i>I live</i>?

00:02:05.780 --> 00:02:06.340
<v Student><b>Vivo.</b>

00:02:06.500 --> 00:02:07.860
<v Teacher><b>Vivo.</b>

00:02:07.860 --> 00:02:12.180
<v Teacher><i>Here</i> in Spanish is <b>aquí</b> or <b>acá</b>.

00:02:12.180 --> 00:02:16.740
<v Teacher><b>Aquí</b> in Spain, and <b>acá</b> in Latin America.

00:02:16.420 --> 00:02:18.180
<v Teacher>Everybody understands both.

00:02:18.180 --> 00:02:21.060
<v Teacher>It's an extremely common word so you don't have to worry

00:02:21.060 --> 00:02:22.900
<v Teacher><b>aquí</b> or <b>acá</b>.

00:02:22.900 --> 00:02:24.260
<v Teacher>So <i>I </i> <i>live here</i>:

00:02:25.500 --> 00:02:26.700
<v Student><b>Vivo aquí.</b>

00:02:26.700 --> 00:02:27.580
<v Teacher><b>Vivo aquí, Vivo acá.</b>

00:02:28.620 --> 00:02:28.940
<v Teacher>Good.

00:02:28.940 --> 00:02:30.860
<v Teacher><i>I don't live here</i>:

00:02:30.860 --> 00:02:32.220
<v Student><b>No vivo aquí.</b>

00:02:32.220 --> 00:02:33.099
<v Teacher>Good.

00:02:33.099 --> 00:02:34.780
<v Teacher><i>But he lives here</i>.

00:02:34.780 --> 00:02:37.340
<v Teacher>And let's stress that because we're contrasting.

00:02:37.340 --> 00:02:39.420
<v Teacher><i>But HE lives here:</i>

00:02:40.060 --> 00:02:41.060
<v Student><b>Pero él</b>?

00:02:41.060 --> 00:02:42.060
<v Teacher>Yes.

00:02:42.060 --> 00:02:44.060
<v Student><b>Vive aquí.</b>

00:02:44.060 --> 00:02:44.460
<v Teacher>Good.

00:02:44.460 --> 00:02:45.980
<v Teacher>Let's make it all together.

00:02:45.980 --> 00:02:49.260
<v Teacher><i>I don't live here, but he lives here:</i>

00:02:49.260 --> 00:02:53.299
<v Student><b>No vivo aquí, pero él vive aquí.</b>

00:02:53.299 --> 00:02:53.620
<v Teacher>Good.

00:02:53.620 --> 00:02:56.019
<v Teacher>And don't be afraid to try the soft <i>b</i>.

00:02:56.019 --> 00:03:00.019
<v Teacher>If it's too difficult then it's not a problem that you pronounce the /<i>vuh</i>/.

00:03:00.019 --> 00:03:03.700
<v Teacher>Maybe you want to pronounce the /<i>vuh</i>/ at the beginning and then see what happens.

00:03:03.560 --> 00:03:09.560
<v Teacher>But the more you pronounce like how people are speaking around you, the more you understand.

00:03:09.560 --> 00:03:10.840
<v Teacher><i>To know </i>is:

00:03:12.260 --> 00:03:13.140
<v Student><b>Saver.</b>

00:03:13.140 --> 00:03:13.940
<v Teacher><b>Saber.</b> This is a <i>b</i>.

00:03:13.940 --> 00:03:15.700
<v Student>It's a <i>b</i>, <b>saber</b>.

00:03:15.780 --> 00:03:16.500
<v Teacher><b>Saber.</b>

00:03:16.500 --> 00:03:17.220
<v Teacher>This is a <i>b</i>

00:03:17.220 --> 00:03:19.140
<v Teacher>so you're not going to pronounce a <i>v</i>.

00:03:19.140 --> 00:03:20.580
<v Teacher>Saber.

00:03:20.160 --> 00:03:22.800
<v Teacher>So we have <b>vivir</b>, <i>to live</i>. And

00:03:22.800 --> 00:03:27.600
<v Teacher>we need to open up the association of the letter <i>v</i> to include that soft <i>b</i>.

00:03:27.600 --> 00:03:30.400
<v Teacher>Maybe you look up the word in the dictionary for summer

00:03:30.320 --> 00:03:33.120
<v Teacher>which is <b>verano</b> or /<i>berano</i>/.

00:03:33.120 --> 00:03:39.520
<v Teacher>Now if you just program your mind with <b>verano</b> maybe you won't get it when you hear /<i>berano/</i>.

00:03:39.160 --> 00:03:44.120
<v Teacher>So it always makes sense to pronounce the words the way people around you are pronouncing.

00:03:44.120 --> 00:03:48.200
<v Teacher>So if you are practicing Spanish with Colombians, take their accent.

00:03:48.040 --> 00:03:55.720
<v Teacher>If you are practicing with people from Rio de la Plata, Buenos Aries, Montevideo, who have kind of a particular accent, take that accent as well.

00:03:55.720 --> 00:03:59.240
<v Teacher>If you're practicing with people from Madrid, take their accent.

00:03:59.060 --> 00:04:04.260
<v Teacher>The more you speak like the people you're listening to, the easier you understand.

00:04:04.260 --> 00:04:06.579
<v Teacher><b>Vivir</b>, <i>to live</i>.

00:04:06.579 --> 00:04:08.579
<v Teacher>How is: <i>we live</i>?

00:04:08.780 --> 00:04:09.820
<v Student><b>Vivimos.</b>

00:04:09.820 --> 00:04:13.340
<v Teacher><b>Vivimos.</b> There we have the <i>i</i> popping up: <b>vivimos</b>.

00:04:13.340 --> 00:04:15.980
<v Teacher>But for the other versions, we’re going to have the /<i>e</i>/.

00:04:15.980 --> 00:04:17.580
<v Teacher>So <i>he lives</i>:

00:04:17.580 --> 00:04:18.620
<v Student><b>Veve.</b>

00:04:18.620 --> 00:04:20.780
<v Teacher>Some vowel harmony you're making there,

00:04:21.680 --> 00:04:27.280
<v Teacher><b>Vivir</b>? The /<i>e</i>/ is correct but you changed the beginning to match that /<i>e</i>/.

00:04:27.280 --> 00:04:28.000
<v Student><b>Vive.</b>

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:30.160
<v Teacher>Good. <b>Vive.</b> Before you said <b>veve.</b>

00:04:30.160 --> 00:04:38.620
<v Teacher>This is vowel harmony again. So you must consciously take off that ending, see what you're left with, <b>vivir</b> - <b>viv</b>, and put on your ending: <b>vive</b> - <i>e</i>.

00:04:38.620 --> 00:04:40.220
<v Teacher>Good.

00:04:40.220 --> 00:04:42.460
<v Teacher><i>They live</i>, or <i>you guys</i>:

00:04:43.520 --> 00:04:44.400
<v Student><b>Viven.</b>

00:04:45.759 --> 00:04:48.479
<v Teacher><b>Viven.</b> <i>They live here</i>:

00:04:48.479 --> 00:04:49.520
<v Student><b>Viven aquí</b>.

00:04:49.520 --> 00:04:51.520
<v Teacher><b>Viven aquí, viven acá.</b>

00:04:51.520 --> 00:04:54.879
<v Teacher>The word for <i>where</i> is <b>dónde</b>, <b>dónde</b>.

00:04:54.879 --> 00:04:57.280
<v Teacher>So how would you say: ¿<i>where do </i> <i>they live?:</i>

00:04:58.120 --> 00:04:59.880
<v Student>¿<b>Dónde viven?</b>

00:04:59.880 --> 00:05:03.640
<v Teacher><i>I want to know where they live</i>:

00:05:03.640 --> 00:05:07.240
<v Student><b>Quiero saber dónde viven.</b>

00:05:07.240 --> 00:05:10.840
<v Teacher>Good. <b>Quiero saber dónde viven.</b> Good.

00:05:10.699 --> 00:05:15.419
<v Teacher><b>Entender</b> is <i>to understand</i>.

00:05:15.419 --> 00:05:16.300
<v Teacher><b>Entender</b>.

00:05:16.300 --> 00:05:22.139
<v Teacher>We said we can use <b>comprender</b> as well, which might be easy to remember, but <b>entender</b> is much more common.

00:05:22.139 --> 00:05:24.220
<v Teacher>How do you say: <i>I understand</i>?

00:05:25.520 --> 00:05:26.560
<v Student><b>Entiendo.</b>

00:05:26.560 --> 00:05:31.280
<v Teacher><b>Entiendo.</b> Good. The <i>e</i> splits: <b>entender</b>-<b>entiendo</b>. <i>He understands</i>:

00:05:31.280 --> 00:05:32.639
<v Student><b>Entiende.</b>

00:05:32.639 --> 00:05:35.900
<v Teacher><b>Entiende.</b> <i>He doesn't understand</i>:

00:05:35.900 --> 00:05:37.900
<v Student><b>No entiende.</b>

00:05:37.900 --> 00:05:41.900
<v Teacher><i>Why doesn't he understand?</i>

00:05:41.900 --> 00:05:43.900
<v Student>¿<b>Por qué no entiende?</b>

00:05:43.900 --> 00:05:47.400
<v Teacher>¿<b>Por qué no entiende?</b> Good. <i>I want to know why he doesn't understand</i>:

00:05:47.400 --> 00:05:51.400
<v Student><b>Quiero saber por qué no entiende.</b>

00:05:51.400 --> 00:05:55.639
<v Teacher><b>Quiero saber por qué no entiende.</b> How do you think you would say: <i>we understand</i>?

00:05:55.639 --> 00:05:59.960
<v Student><b>Entendemos.</b>

00:05:59.960 --> 00:06:01.560
<v Teacher>Good.

00:06:01.560 --> 00:06:03.800
<v Teacher>So for -<i>er</i> verbs we have -<i>emos</i>.

00:06:03.800 --> 00:06:07.960
<v Teacher>So this is the only difference in the entire language between -<i>er</i> verbs and -<i>ir</i> verbs.

00:06:07.960 --> 00:06:10.360
<v Teacher>For everything else they are exactly the same.

00:06:10.060 --> 00:06:13.500
<v Teacher>But for <i>we</i> in the present tense, we get -<i>imos</i> and -<i>emos</i>.

00:06:13.500 --> 00:06:15.020
<v Teacher><b>Vivir</b>-<b>vivimos</b>,

00:06:15.020 --> 00:06:16.940
<v Teacher><b>venir</b>-<b>venimos</b>,

00:06:16.940 --> 00:06:19.419
<v Teacher><b>preferir</b>-<b>preferimos</b>, and then for -<i>er</i> verbs -<i>emos</i>.

00:06:19.240 --> 00:06:23.800
<v Teacher><b>Entender</b>-<b>entendemos</b>. <b>Perder</b>, which we said was <i>to lose</i>.

00:06:23.800 --> 00:06:27.960
<v Teacher>So how do you say: <i>we lose</i>?

00:06:28.540 --> 00:06:29.660
<v Student><b>Perdemos.</b>

00:06:29.660 --> 00:06:30.620
<v Teacher>Perdemos.

00:06:30.780 --> 00:06:31.340
<v Teacher><b>Perdemos.</b> Good.

00:06:31.340 --> 00:06:35.500
<v Teacher>The word for <i>always</i> in Spanish is <b>siempre</b>.

00:06:35.500 --> 00:06:39.020
<v Teacher>So how would you say: <i>we always lose</i>?

00:06:39.000 --> 00:06:44.040
<v Teacher>(You can put the <b>siempre</b> before or afterwards.)

00:06:44.040 --> 00:06:46.520
<v Student><b>Siempre perdemos.</b>

00:06:46.520 --> 00:06:49.080
<v Teacher><b>Siempre perdemos.</b> <i>We always lose.</i> Or <b>perdemos siempre</b>.
